  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>In September 2023, the FDA updated the prescribing label for Ozempic. The change added a single word to the list of post-marketing adverse reactions: ileus. Intestinal blockage. The kind that can kill you. The agency had received reports from patients whose intestines had stopped moving. The clinical trials that got semaglutide approved had enrolled thousands of patients over years of study. None of them had flagged this.</p>
  <p>That gap between the trial and the label update is the story of GLP-1 drug safety in miniature. The cardiovascular benefits are real. The weight loss is real. The story is about the architecture of evidence itself: who builds it, what questions it's designed to answer, and what happens when a drug tested on a few thousand people reaches more than 30 million.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-trials-found-what-they-looked-for" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Trials Found What They Looked For</h2>
  <p>The pivotal weight-loss trial for semaglutide, STEP 1, enrolled 1,961 participants over 68 weeks. They lost a mean of 14.9% of their body weight. The trial was designed, monitored, and analyzed by Novo Nordisk. It was powered to detect weight loss. It was not powered to detect a 1-in-500 adverse event that takes two years to manifest.</p>
  <p>The SELECT trial was larger and longer: 17,604 patients with pre-existing cardiovascular disease, followed for a mean of 39.8 months. It found a 20% reduction in major adverse cardiovascular events. Hazard ratio 0.80, confidence interval 0.72 to 0.90, p less than 0.001. Dismissing that because Novo Nordisk funded the trial would be intellectually dishonest.</p>
  <p>But SELECT was designed to find cardiovascular benefit. It enrolled patients who already had heart disease. It ran until enough cardiac events accumulated to reach statistical significance. Adverse events leading to permanent discontinuation were twice as common in the semaglutide group: 16.6% versus 8.2%.</p>
  <p>That discontinuation gap got one sentence in the published paper.</p>
</section>

<section id="real-world-patients-found-what-trials-missed" class="reveal">
  <h2>Real-World Patients Found What Trials Missed</h2>
  <p>Dr. Caroline Apovian, co-director of the Center for Weight Management at Brigham and Women's Hospital, told Healthline that her team noticed ileus in semaglutide patients well before the FDA's label change. By mid-2023, the FDA's adverse event reporting system had logged 20 cases of intestinal blockage with semaglutide, including two deaths. A 2023 study in <em>Gastroenterology</em> identified a 25% higher ileus risk in real-world data compared to trial populations. That study was funded by Eli Lilly, which manufactures semaglutide's direct competitor. Worth noting. Also worth noting: the signal was real regardless of who paid to find it.</p>
  <p>Muscle loss told a stranger story. It was sitting in STEP 1's own body-composition substudy: roughly 39% of the weight patients lost came from lean mass, not fat. That ratio is consistent with what's observed in caloric restriction and bariatric surgery, where lean mass typically accounts for 25–40% of total weight lost. The open question is whether GLP-1 drugs accelerate the problem in populations already vulnerable to sarcopenia. A 2025 Endocrine Society presentation found that older adults and women lost the most muscle, and that excessive lean mass loss blunted semaglutide's benefits for blood sugar control. A network meta-analysis of 22 randomized trials confirmed that semaglutide 2.4 mg is among the least effective GLP-1 agents at preserving lean mass. Whether this is clinically meaningful or merely proportional remains unstudied at the scale it deserves.</p>
  <p>The suicidal ideation signal showed the surveillance system doing what it's supposed to do. In July 2023, the European Medicines Agency opened a formal review after Iceland reported cases of suicidal thoughts in patients on semaglutide and liraglutide. Nine months later, the EMA concluded that available evidence did not support a causal link. A <em>Nature Medicine</em> study of 240,000 patients found no association. The answer, for now, is reassuring. The timeline is not: nine months is a long time when a drug class is adding millions of users per quarter.</p>
  <p>SUSTAIN-6, a cardiovascular trial for semaglutide in diabetic patients, found retinopathy complications in 3.0% of the semaglutide group versus 1.8% on placebo. This appeared in the drug label. It did not appear in most media coverage of semaglutide's cardiovascular benefits. Meanwhile, a large population-based cohort study from Taiwan, published in <em>Diabetes Care</em> in 2024, found no statistically significant increase in thyroid cancer risk over a median four-year follow-up, despite semaglutide carrying the FDA's most serious warning for thyroid C-cell tumors based on rodent data. The Taiwan study was funded by government grants, its authors declared no conflicts, and it remains the cleanest data point on this question. It cuts against the alarming narrative.</p>
  <p>A 1-in-1,000 adverse event is nearly impossible to detect in a trial of 2,000 patients. At 10 million prescriptions, that same rate produces 10,000 cases. Pre-approval trials are designed to detect common effects. Rare but serious harms become visible only at population scale, through a surveillance system that captures as little as 1–10% of actual events.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-endorsers-cash-the-same-checks" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Endorsers Cash the Same Checks</h2>
  <p>The American Diabetes Association's highest corporate recognition, "Banting Circle Elite," goes to supporters contributing at least $1 million annually. Novo Nordisk holds that designation. The company sponsors the ADA's Scientific Sessions, co-funded the Know Diabetes by Heart initiative with the American Heart Association, and in 2025 became the inaugural supporter of the ADA's new Obesity Association division with a multi-year funding commitment of undisclosed size. The ADA's guidelines recommend GLP-1 drugs as first-line agents for obesity and type 2 diabetes.</p>
  <p>The Endocrine Society's clinical practice guidelines for obesity pharmacotherapy are written by panels whose members routinely disclose consulting relationships with Novo Nordisk and Eli Lilly. A 2022 supplement reviewing current obesity treatment guidelines in the <em>American Journal of Managed Care</em> carried a clean disclosure: funded by Novo Nordisk Inc.</p>
  <p>Funding conflicts do not automatically invalidate guidance. The cardiovascular data from SELECT would stand up in front of any independent panel. But there is a difference between a recommendation supported by independent evidence and a recommendation issued by an institution collecting seven-figure checks from the manufacturer. That difference matters most when the long-term safety data comes almost entirely from the manufacturer's own trials.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-critics-have-their-own-revenue-streams" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Critics Have Their Own Revenue Streams</h2>
  <p>Robert Lustig, the endocrinologist who has been loudest about GLP-1 muscle-wasting risks, maintains consulting relationships with supplement companies and derives substantial income from books arguing that processed food is the root of metabolic disease. His incentives run directly against pharmaceutical solutions to obesity. That doesn't make him wrong. It makes him interested.</p>
  <p>Peter Attia's podcast and coaching programs frequently question pharmaceutical approaches to metabolic health. He operates a business model that competes with the drugs he critiques. The 2023 <em>Gastroenterology</em> study identifying higher ileus risk was funded by Eli Lilly. The network meta-analysis confirming lean mass loss across GLP-1 agents included authors with competing pharma affiliations.</p>
  <p>The institutional voices endorsing GLP-1 safety are funded by the manufacturers. The contrarian voices questioning it are funded by competitors, supplement companies, or direct-to-consumer health businesses. The cleanest data comes from places like the Taiwan cohort: publicly funded, no declared conflicts, adequate sample size. Almost nobody is funding more studies like it.</p>
</section>

<section id="faers-runs-on-volunteerism-and-hope" class="reveal">
  <h2>FAERS Runs on Volunteerism and Hope</h2>
  <p>The FDA's Adverse Event Reporting System is a passive, voluntary system. Only manufacturers are required to submit reports, and only for events they learn about. The FDA estimates FAERS captures between 1% and 10% of actual adverse events for most drug classes.</p>
  <p>When the FDA updated the semaglutide label for ileus, the agency noted that because reports are voluntary, it is not always possible to reliably estimate frequency or establish a causal relationship. The regulator, in official language, acknowledging that its own surveillance system cannot determine how common a serious adverse event actually is.</p>
  <p>An October 2025 Gallup poll found that 12.4% of American adults were taking a GLP-1 drug for weight loss. More than 30 million people. If the true FAERS reporting rate for ileus is 5% of actual cases, the 20 reports in the database represent 400 real events. If it's 1%, the number is 2,000. More recent pharmacovigilance literature suggests the higher end of that capture range (5–10%) is more likely for serious events involving high-profile drug classes. Nobody knows the precise denominator, because the system was never designed to find out.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-gap-nobody-is-assigned-to-close" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Gap Nobody Is Assigned to Close</h2>
  <p>The pre-approval trials were too short and too narrow to detect rare long-term harms. The post-market surveillance system captures a fraction of actual events. The professional organizations endorsing these drugs are funded by the companies selling them. The independent researchers questioning them have their own entanglements.</p>
  <p>Nobody is required to conduct independent, long-term, adequately powered safety studies after a drug reaches the market. The manufacturer has no incentive to look for problems. The regulator lacks the funding and statutory authority to mandate them. The professional organizations have financial relationships that compromise their independence. And the patients are the ones generating the data, one voluntary adverse event report at a time, into a system that captures almost none of it.</p>
  <p>Three reforms have been proposed by regulatory scholars and public health researchers. Mandatory independent long-term registries for drug classes that reach population-scale prescribing, triggered when a drug crosses a threshold of, say, 5 million prescriptions. Pre-specified post-market study requirements with public funding and independent oversight, so the FDA can compel studies designed to answer questions the manufacturer would prefer not to ask. And conflict-of-interest firewalls in guideline committees, so that the ADA's Banting Circle Elite status is disclosed to patients and prescribers at the point of care, not buried in annual reports.</p>
  <p>None are in place. The evidence infrastructure was built for a world where drugs reached thousands of patients, not tens of millions. The drugs have outgrown the system designed to watch them.</p>
</section>

